The Reliability pillar.

Reliability is the pillar about meeting your uptime and recovery targets, and its checklist pulls modules three, eight, and thirteen together.

Be distributed across A-Zs for every production tier, so Auto Scaling Groups span all A-Zs, R-D-S is Multi-A-Z, ElastiCache is Multi-A-Z, and the A-L-B uses cross-zone load balancing. Keep compute stateless, with sessions in ElastiCache, files in S3, and secrets in Secrets Manager, so local disk holds nothing of value and any instance can be replaced. Build in automatic recovery, where Auto Scaling self-heals failed instances, A-L-B health checks remove bad targets, E-C-2 Auto Recovery handles host failures, and the E-C-S scheduler replaces failed tasks. Manage your service quotas, requesting increases before you hit them and alarming on quota usage through the Service Quotas console. Choose and test a D-R strategy, Backup and Restore, Pilot Light, Warm Standby, or Active-Active per workload, with quarterly drills. And handle backpressure with S-Q-S to absorb spikes, exponential backoff with jitter, and idempotency so that a retry is always safe.

The design principles: automatically recover from failure, test recovery procedures, scale horizontally, stop guessing capacity, and manage change through automation. The mental model is: assume everything fails, and make failure a non-event. A single instance, A-Z, or dependency dying should degrade gracefully, not page anyone. The cue: survive an A-Z outage, no single point of failure, recover automatically, or meet an R-T-O and R-P-O, all point to this pillar.
